                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 Standard Vacuum Oil Company/46:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Salisbury</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-03T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 3, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 3—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>484. Reference paragraph 1 of Embassy’s 478, July 31, noon. Colonel Marston
                    states that he prefers that his opinion be expressed <pb facs="0431" n="427"
                        xml:id="pg_427"/> as follows: he believes that guards should be furnished in
                    the interests of American trade, provided that there are no diplomatic
                    objections and provided that the guard can be placed on a separate convoying
                    tug.</p>
                <p>Sent to Ambassador [aboard] <hi rend="italic">Luzon</hi>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Salisbury</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
